ur photodynamical analysis also reveals that Kepler-138 c (with a Rc\,=\,1.51\,{$\pm$}\,0.04\,R{$\oplus$} and a \$\$\{M\}\_\{\{\{\{\textbackslash rm\{c\}\}\}\}\}=2.\{3\}\_\{-0.5\}\^\{+0.6\}\textbackslash,\{M\}\_\{\textbackslash oplus \}\$\$) is a slightly warmer twin of Kepler-138 d (that is, another water world in the same system) and we infer the presence of Kepler-138 e, a likely non-transiting planet at the inner edge of the habitable zone.},
